{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"25d46ba9-13f9-4292-9632-253b2ce9b0da","content":"CLR activation logs diagnose **runtime loading/selection** issues (e.g., wrong CLR version, missing runtime). They won't help with a `NullReferenceException`, which is an application-level bug that occurs after the runtime has already loaded successfully.\n\n**To diagnose your NullReferenceException, you'd want:**\n- The full stack trace from the exception\n- Application logs or a crash dump\n\n**CLR activation logs would help if you saw:**\n- \"Failed to load the runtime\" errors\n- Wrong .NET version being picked up\n- Missing framework errors at startup\n\nCould you share the stack trace or crash dump? That'll point directly to the null reference.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"11ce2045-c6e9-4b55-9837-52f465faa9be","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking me to analyze CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException in their .NET app. However, they haven't provided any CLR activation logs, and there don't appear to be any files in the working directory to analyze.\n\nLet me check if there are any files in the current working directory first, and also note that CLR activation logs are about runtime selection/loading, not about NullReferenceExceptions. But let me first check what's available.","outputTokens":273,"requestId":"9423:2544DD:34CEB9:3E37A4:69E82452"},"id":"404a7463-7bee-467b-89cc-f7e0220917eb","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:28:58.626Z","parentId":"8c8bcbfa-64c6-4d4f-b06b-7ba816878c21"}
